(40, 25, 8, 18, 18, 5, 5, 'our lamps are gone out', 'Light and Darkness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of light being extinguished. In Matthew, the foolish find their lamps gone out, paralleling Job''s assertion that the light of the wicked shall be put out.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 9, 19, 49, 7, 9, 'buy for yourselves', 'Redemption and Personal Responsibility', 'Both passages emphasize the inability to share redemption. In Matthew, the wise virgins refuse to share their oil, paralleling the idea in Psalms that one cannot redeem another''s soul.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 9, 66, 3, 17, 18, 'buy for yourselves', 'Wisdom and Spiritual Wealth', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking true wealth. In Matthew, the wise emphasize the need to procure their own resources, while Revelation advises buying true riches from Christ, contrasting material wealth with spiritual richness.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 9, 23, 55, 6, 7, 'buy for yourselves', 'Seeking and Preparation', 'This connection highlights the importance of being prepared and seeking what is necessary. Both passages emphasize the urgency of taking action—whether it is buying oil or seeking the Lord—before it is too late.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 9, 26, 14, 20, 20, 'buy for yourselves', 'Individual Responsibility in Righteousness', 'This connection highlights the theme of individual accountability in righteousness. Both passages emphasize that personal righteousness is essential for salvation, as seen in the wise virgins'' need to procure their own oil and the mention of Noah, Daniel, and Job delivering only their own souls.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 9, 24, 15, 1, 1, 'not enough for us and you', 'Rejection of Unpreparedness', 'This connection highlights the theme of unpreparedness and the consequences of seeking help too late. In both passages, there is a sense of urgency in addressing one''s own needs before relying on others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 9, 26, 14, 14, 16, 'buy for yourselves', 'Individual Responsibility in Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that individuals are responsible for their own actions and cannot rely on others for salvation or deliverance. In Matthew, the wise virgins refuse to share their oil, indicating that each must procure their own readiness. Similarly, Ezekiel highlights that even righteous individuals like Noah, Daniel, and Job can only save themselves, not their families.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 9, 44, 8, 22, 22, NULL, 'Repentance and Personal Responsibility', 'This connection highlights the theme of personal responsibility in seeking forgiveness. Both passages emphasize the need for individuals to take action for their own spiritual well-being.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 10, 42, 13, 25, 25, 'the door was shut', 'Closed Door Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of a closed door representing exclusion from the kingdom. In Matthew, the door is shut after the bridegroom arrives, while in Luke, the master shuts the door, denying entry to those outside.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 10, 40, 24, 44, 44, 'ready', 'Readiness for the Coming', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of being ready for the unexpected arrival of the Son of man. The readiness mentioned in Matthew 24:44 directly relates to the consequences of unpreparedness illustrated in Matthew 25:10.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 10, 42, 12, 36, 37, 'the bridegroom came', 'Readiness for the Bridegroom', 'This connection highlights the theme of readiness for the return of the bridegroom. Both passages emphasize the importance of being prepared and vigilant for his arrival.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 10, 60, 1, 13, 13, 'they that were ready', 'Readiness for Christ''s Return', 'This connection highlights the theme of being prepared for the coming of Christ. Both passages emphasize the importance of readiness and vigilance in anticipation of the revelation of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 10, 1, 7, 16, 16, 'the door was shut', 'Shutting of the Door', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine closure in both passages. In Matthew, the door is shut after the bridegroom arrives, while in Genesis, the Lord shuts Noah and his family in the ark.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 10, 19, 95, 11, 11, NULL, 'Entry and Rest Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of entering into a state of rest or celebration. In Matthew 25:10, those who are ready enter the marriage, while Psalms 95:11 speaks of not entering into rest, suggesting a parallel between readiness and the consequences of unpreparedness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 10, 30, 8, 12, 13, NULL, 'Connection of Readiness and Thirst', 'This connection highlights the theme of readiness and the consequences of unpreparedness. Both passages emphasize a sense of urgency and the dire outcomes for those who are not ready, as seen in the ''fair virgins'' fainting for thirst.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 11, 40, 7, 21, 23, 'Lord, Lord', 'Call to the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''Lord, Lord,'' highlighting the distinction between mere verbal acknowledgment of Jesus and the necessity of genuine obedience to God''s will. This connection underscores the theme of true discipleship versus superficial faith.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 11, 58, 12, 16, 17, 'Lord, Lord, open to us', 'Rejection and Seeking Access', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking access after a missed opportunity. Both passages emphasize the urgency of seeking acceptance, as seen in the virgins'' plea and Esau''s regret.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 12, 43, 10, 27, 27, 'I know you not', 'Knowledge of the Believer', 'This connection highlights the theme of knowledge and recognition. In Matthew 25:12, the speaker states, ''I know you not,'' contrasting with John 10:27, where Jesus affirms, ''I know them.''', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 12, 46, 8, 3, 3, 'I know you not', 'Knowledge of God and Believers', 'This connection highlights the theme of being known by God. In Matthew 25:12, the phrase ''I know you not'' contrasts with 1 Corinthians 8:3, which states that those who love God are known by Him.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 12, 55, 2, 19, 19, 'I know you not', 'Divine Knowledge and Recognition', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine knowledge and recognition. In Matthew 25:12, the phrase ''I know you not'' contrasts with 2 Timothy 2:19, which states ''The Lord knoweth them that are his,'' emphasizing the importance of being recognized by God.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 12, 42, 13, 26, 30, 'I know you not', 'Rejection of the Unrecognized', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of rejection based on a lack of recognition. In each case, the speaker declares, ''I know you not,'' indicating a separation from those who presume familiarity.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 12, 19, 1, 6, 6, 'I know you not', 'Knowledge of the Righteous and Ungodly', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine knowledge regarding individuals. In Matthew 25:12, the phrase ''I know you not'' contrasts with Psalms 1:6, where ''the Lord knoweth the way of the righteous'' emphasizes God''s awareness of the righteous versus the ungodly.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 12, 19, 5, 5, 5, 'I know you not', 'Rejection of the Wicked', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine rejection. Both passages emphasize that those who are foolish or engage in iniquity are not recognized or accepted by God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 12, 43, 9, 31, 31, 'I know you not', 'God''s Response to Believers', 'Both passages emphasize God''s relationship with individuals based on their actions. Matthew 25:12 indicates a lack of recognition for those not known by God, while John 9:31 highlights that God hears those who worship Him and do His will.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 13, 40, 24, 42, 44, 'Watch therefore', 'Readiness for the Lord''s Coming', 'Both passages emphasize the need to ''watch'' for the coming of the Son of man, highlighting the uncertainty of the timing. They stress the importance of being prepared, as the exact hour is unknown.', 'theme', 0.489, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 13, 66, 16, 15, 15, 'Watch therefore, for ye know', 'Watchfulness and Preparedness', 'Both passages emphasize the need for vigilance in anticipation of the coming of the Son of man. The call to ''watch'' in Matthew aligns with the warning in Revelation to keep one''s garments, suggesting readiness for an unexpected arrival.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 13, 52, 5, 6, 6, 'watch therefore, for ye know neither', 'Vigilance and Readiness', 'Both passages emphasize the need for vigilance and readiness in anticipation of the coming of the Son of man. They encourage believers to remain alert and sober, highlighting the uncertainty of the timing of His return.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 25, 13, 42, 21, 36, 36, 'Watch therefore', 'Call to Watchfulness', 'Both passages emphasize the need to ''watch'' in anticipation of the Son of man''s coming. They highlight the importance of being prepared and vigilant as the exact time of His return is unknown.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
